bio:
I love experimenting with cost-effective solutions for building, re-building, modifying and fine-tuning printers. (and, of course, using them to print amazing things). My own mod designs and remixes for my 4 printers are in bold below. Most are published here in Thingiverse (see under "designs").
Here it goes, more or less in chronological order:

1) Grabber Prusa I3 (built)

  • Servo-based auto bed tramming (a.k.a. leveling)
  • Filament run-out detector
  • Lateral glass support
  • Z-axis anti-backlash
  • Replaced stepper drivers with DRV8825
  • TFT28 touch screen panel

2) MPCNC 24" X 24", Dewalt 660 (built)

  • Arduino/Ramps Support
  • Added reinforced center hub
  • Cable chain support
  • TFT28 touch screen support

3) Solidoodle 4 (re-built)

  • Replaced all stock MXL pulleys and belts with GT2 and 16 tooth pulleys
  • Replaced all stock rods with smooth chrome hardened rods
  • Replaced stock carriages with redesigned carriages (Lawsy remix)
  • Removed rod/pulley Y axis movement transfer with direct dual stepper motors drive
  • Added Bed stabilizer rod (remix)
  • Added Temperature controlled printing chamber (thermostat panel)
  • Replaced Printrboard with Arduino / Ramps 1.4 + DRV8825 stepper drivers

4) Delta 3KU (re-built)

  • Stepper drivers replaced with DRV8825
  • Replaced stock MXL pulleys and belts with GT2 and 16 tooth pulleys
  • Replaced stock micro-switch end stops with optical ones
  • Added effector-mounted duct for blower

5) BQ Hephestos 2

  • Just bought a pre-owned - researching broken M5 Igus Z Nut solution

I am a math student and automotive machinist. My interests include cad and cg, manufacturing and operations, open source and philanthropy, business management and entrepreneurialism, and finally, desktop manufacturing and 3DP.

As an academic I work in differential geometry and topology, logic and computation, game theory and economics, functional programming knowledge and databases, and most lately, finance and business.

As a maker, I like to design interesting geometries, mischevious electronics, and machine shop tooling. I've been away from actually making things for a long time now, and I miss it dearly.

My mission here is to

1) Design and share neat doodads, and grow as a designer and maker.
2) Learn as much as I can about design customization and design automation.
3) Meet dedicated and insightful makers, and learn as much as I can from them.

To my thought, we can wade the through barriers of knowledge and economics surrounding cad and 3dp. In time, we will make the associated skills and capital goods easy to acquire, and very affordable. I have faith that as we continue to do this, we'll continue to see an amazing growth in personal creativity and prosperity, all over the world. I'd love to have a part in making that possible!

It is an honor to join this community.

Born in 1850 in Dublin, James Purcell had lived a long life filled with hardships that would likely have killed the average person.
Whilst most of his life is shrouded in mystery and intrigue, what can be released has been through his journals.
He moved to Bristol in 1860 where he spent his early years in the local common school with other children who lived in the area. After gaining the eye of a professor in Bristol James became his understudy and began his education in Mythology.
In 1872 James was betrothed to the professors' daughter but after a night at the theatre they were attacked by an unknown assailant and his fiancée was killed.
When the professor disappeared James was convicted of both his and his daughter's murders - how he escaped the hangman's noose is a matter of great speculation and much secrecy.
In 2011 James returned to England to become managing director of Æther Technology and Transport.

Steve Lambert has worked alongside artists and activists in 16 countries on 4 continents helping them to effect power. Trained in the arts, he is known for large scale, public projects that engage new audiences on difficult topics through the social science of comedy, games, theater, and democratic participation.

Lambert is the co-founder and co-director of the Center for Artistic Activism, a research and training institute helping activists be more creative and artists be more effective.

As an artist, Lambert’s work has been shown both nationally and internationally, from art galleries to Times Square to protest marches, featured in four documentary films, and over two dozen books, and collected by museums and The Library of Congress. Lambert has presented at the United Nations several times. His research is included in a United Nations report on the impact of advertising on cultural rights, as well as the basis for a book on popular understandings of capitalism.

Over the past five years he's focused on working with sex workers on campaigns for human rights, fighting for safe consumption spaces with people who use drugs like heroin and methamphetamine, and working with Treatment Action Group battling pharmaceutical companies over pricing for HEP-C treatments.

Depuis la rentrée scolaire 2014, le lycée Henri Nominé propose une nouvelle section ULIS Pro (Unité Localisée pour l'Inclusion Scolaire).

Le dispositif permet à des jeunes lycéens présentant des besoins éducatifs particuliers en liaison avec une situation de handicap, d'être accueillis en lycée professionel.

FABULIS est au coeur de cette toute nouvelle section. Le Fablab est destiné aux élèves de l'ULIS pro pour qu'ils puissent développer des projets Artistiques, Scientifiques et en relation avec les nouvelles technologies.

FABULIS est aussi ouvert à toute les personnes fréquentant le lycée Henri Nominé ( élèves, enseignants, personnel administratif et technique).

Les élèves de BTS, BAC Pro, CAP et 3DP sont amenés à travailler dans le même espace que les élèves de l'ULIS Pro. Ainsi ce ne sont pas les élèves en situation de handicap qui sont inclus, mais les autres personnes qui s'intègrent naturellement à ce nouveau dispositif "l'inclusion inversée".
